<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">VEP 0010</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Submission by Jonathan Fisher QC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> (VEP 0010)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">his </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">evidence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">addresses the single issue of whether the right to vote is properly to be considered a human right.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The short answer, in my</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> view</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, is that it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">not. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The prisoner voting debate has been characterised</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> by a failure to distinguish </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">between</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the guarantee to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hold free elections on the one hand, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ner in which free elections are to be held on the other. The former, namely the requirement </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">imposed on a State </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to hold free elections at reasonable intervals, is a fundamental freedom and recognised as a human right. The latter, namely the manner in which an </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">election</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is held and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a citizen’s ability to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">participate in it, is not.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Universal suf</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">frage is the means by which th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e human right requiring the State to hold free elections </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is realised, but it is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a human </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">right itself.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This distinction </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">between the right to hold free elections and a citizen’s ability to participate in an election </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is reflected in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Article 3 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Protocol 1 of the European Convention on Human Rights </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(“the Convention”) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">which provides as follows:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ARTICLE 3</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Right to free elections</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The High Contracting Parties undertake to hold free elections at</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reasonable intervals by secret ballot, under conditions which will</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ensure the free expression of the opinion of the people in the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">choice of the legislature.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The omission to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">articulate </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a human right guaranteeing an individual’s right to participate in free elections was deliberate.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> At a meeting of the Committee of Experts on Human Rights</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (“the Committee”)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> at the Council of Europe on 3 February 1950, Sir Oscar Dowson (the UK’s representative) explained:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“ … It is probable that suffrage is as wide in the United Kingdom as in any other country; yet even in the United Kingdom it is inaccurate to speak of suffrage as “universal”. In no State is the right to vote enjoyed even by citizens without qualifications. The qualifications required differ from State to State, and it is our view that the variety of circumstances to be considered may justify the imposition of a variety of qualifications, as a condition of the exercise of suffrage ...”</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ven if a reference to universal suffrage had been included in Article 3 Protocol 1, the other signatory </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">countries</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> were clear that this would not confer on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">citizen a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">human </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">righ</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t to vote in every circumstance</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. The response of the other member States was </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">summarised </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Committee’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">draft </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">on 15 February 1950 in the following terms:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“The United Kingdom representative stated that his Government was opposed to the insertion of an Article of this kind in the Convention by reason of the practical difficulties which would thereby arise, particularly over the definition of the term “universal suffrage”, the right to vote being, in all countries, subject to restrictions [...]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The other Committee members, however, were of the opinion that the term “universal suffrage” had a sufficiently clear and precise meaning for the European countries and did not exclude the usual restriction on the right to vote. The members felt, moreover, that even if universal suffrage and secret ballot was not an absolute guarantee of democracy, it nevertheless constituted an important guarantee which merited protection by the Convention.”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Two significant points emerge from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a consideration of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">this passage. First, as already noted, signatory </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">countries </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">did not consider that the notion of universal suffrage excluded any restriction on the right to vote. Secondly, the significance of the reference to universal suffrage is not the articulation of a human right to vote, but rather the recognition of the means </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">or mechanism </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">by which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">free election</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">secured.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This understanding was re-iterated in 1966 in Article 25 of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">provide</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“Every citizen shall have the right and the opportunity, without any of the distinctions mentioned in article 2 and without unreasonable restrictions:</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(a) To take part in the conduct of public affairs, directly or through freely chosen representatives;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(b) To vote and to be elected at genuine periodic elections which shall be by universal and equal suffrage and shall be held by secret ballot, guaranteeing the free expression of the will of the electors;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">c) To have access, on general terms of equality, to public service in his country.”</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Thirty years later, this understanding remained unchanged. In 1996, when considering the issue of universal suffrage, the United Nations Office of the Commission for Human Rights made clear in a General Comment that:</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">State reports should describe the rules governing the right to vote, and the application of those rules in the period covered by the report. State reports should also describe factors which impede citizens from exercising the right to vote and the positive measures which have been adopted to overcome these factors.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In their reports, States parties should indicate and explain the legislative provisions which would deprive citizens of their right to vote. The grounds for such deprivation should be objective and reasonable. If conviction for an offence is a basis for suspending the right to vote, the period of such suspension should be proportionate to the offence and the sentence. Persons who are deprived of liberty but who have not been convicted should not be excluded from exercising the right to vote.”</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t is interesting to note that the United Nations Office con</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sidered </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that the loss of a convicted prisoner’s ability to vote </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">was</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> not incompatible with the right of universal suffrage or the holding of free elections </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to secure a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">democratic</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ally elected government. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This understanding is consistent with an </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">approach which safeguards the holding of free elections as a fundamental freedom </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">modern democratic society but stops short of recognising a human right which guarantees to every citizen the ability to participate in this process. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A restriction on a convicted prisoner’s ability to participate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in the democratic process is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">both </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reasonable and objectively </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">justifiable.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Where a person</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’s failure to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">comply with the rules of modern civilized society </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is sufficiently serious to justify the imposition of a custodial sentence, he demonstrates a rejection of the societal norms by which his fellow citizens have chosen to live. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ithdrawal from participation in civil society is an important </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">feature of a custodial sentence, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">inconsistent with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a convicted</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> prisoner’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rejection of these societal norms to permit him to participate in civil society pending his rehabilitation in due course</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> The period of exclusion is proportionate, the length of sentence having been determined in accordance with rationally defensible criteria.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">If a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">person or a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">group of people were to be disenfranchised on grounds which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">we</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">re arbitrary or capricious, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">it would infringe a human right but not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a right to vote. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he infringement would engage a person’s right to be treated equally and not subjected to discrimination on the grounds of sex, race, colour, language, religion, political or other opinion, national or social origin, association with a national minority, property, birth or other status.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> In consequence, a signatory country would infringe its positive obligation under Article 3 Protocol 1 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to hold free elections </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">… </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">under conditions which ensured the free expression of the opinion of the people in the choice of legislature</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">But this is not the same as saying that Article 3 Protocol 1 establishes a discrete human right for an individual to vote which is free-standing. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There is much discussion amongst legal theorists as to how human rights come to be recognised and their substance determined. Theories based on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">John</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Locke’s social contract </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and/or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the existence of natural law rights have given way in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">modern </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">times to a positivist approach, by which human rights are recognised in circumstances where a broad section of society acknowledges this to be the case. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">16.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Applying the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">positivist and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">self-sustaining approach to the recognition of legal norms,  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I believe </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">it is clear that the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">right </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to free elections which guarantee the democratic process is protected as a fundament</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">al freedom whereas </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">an individual’s ability to participate in the process is not.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Declaration of interest</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">: I was a Conservative nominated member of the Commission on a Bill of Rights appointed by the Coalition Government which reported in 2012, and between 20</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">06 and 2010 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I was Chairman of Research of the Society of Conservative Lawyers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">June 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">1</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> See Raab, Strasbourg in the Dock: Prisoner Voting, Human Rights &amp; the Case for Democracy, 2011</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">T</span><span style="color:#300906; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">ravaux </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">préparatoires, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">III, p.182.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">T</span><span style="color:#300906; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">ravaux </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">préparatoires, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">III, p.264.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">General Comment No. 25: The right to participate in public affairs, voting rights and the right of equal access to public service (Art. 25), 12/07/1996,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> CCPR/C/21/Rev.1/Add.7, General Comment No. 25. (General Comments</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">, paragraphs 13 and 14.</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:100%"><tr><td style="background-color:#ffffff; vertical-align:top; width:100%"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Article 14 of the Convention</span></p></body></html>